<header>
=09
<h1>
=09
<a href=3D"https://www.engineeringtoolbox.com/heat-units-d_664.html">
	Units of Heat - BTU, Calorie and Joule
</a>

</h1>
=09
<h2>
	The most common units of heat BTU - British Thermal Unit, Calorie and Joul=
e.
</h2>
</header>
=09
<div id=3D"adSlotDoc1" class=3D"noPrint">
=09
<div>
=09
<!-- adngin-doc1-0 -->
<div id=3D"adngin-doc1-0"></div>
                       =20
</div>

</div>
=09
<div>
	<p>The most common units for heat are</p>
<ul>
<li><i>BTU (Btu) - British Thermal Unit - also known as a "heat unit" in Un=
ited States<br></i></li>
<li><i>Calorie</i></li>
<li><i>Joule</i></li>
</ul>
<h3>BTU - British Thermal Unit</h3>
<p>The unit of heat in the imperial system - the <i>BTU</i> - is</p>
<ul>
<li>the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one pound of wa=
ter through <i>1 <sup>o</sup>F (58.5 <sup>o</sup>F - 59.5 <sup>o</sup>F) </=
i>at sea level <i>(30 inches of mercury).</i></li>
<li><i>1 Btu (British thermal unit) =3D 1055.06 J =3D 107.6 kpm =3D 2.931=
=C3=9710<sup>-4</sup> kWh =3D 0.252 kcal =3D 778.16 ft.lbf =3D 1.05510<sup>=
10</sup> ergs =3D 252 cal =3D 0.293 watt-hours</i></li>
</ul>
<p>An item using one kilowatt-hour of electricity generates <i>3412 Btu</i>=
.</p>
<ul>
<li>one hundred thousand <em>(10<sup>5</sup>)</em> Btu are called a therm</=
li>
</ul>

<div id=3D"adInContent1" class=3D"noPrint">
=09
<div>
=09
<!-- adngin-incontent1-0 -->
<div id=3D"adngin-incontent1-0"></div>
                   =20
</div>

</div>

<h3>Calorie</h3>
<p>A calorie is commonly defined as</p>
<ul>
<li>the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one gram of wat=
er <i>1 <sup>o</sup>C</i></li>
<li>the kilogram calorie, large calorie, food calorie, Calorie (capital C) =
or just calorie (lowercase c) is the amount of energy required to raise the=
 temperature of one kilogram of water by one degree Celsius</li>
<li><em>1 calorie (cal) =3D 1/860 international watthour (Wh)</em></li>
<li><i>1 kcal =3D 4186.8 J =3D 426.9 kp m =3D 1.163=C3=9710<sup>-3</sup> kW=
h =3D 3.088 ft lb<sub>f</sub> =3D 3.9683 Btu =3D 1000 cal</i></li>
</ul>
<p>Be aware that alternative definitions&nbsp;exists - in short:&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
<li>Thermochemical calorie &nbsp;</li>
<li>4&nbsp;=C2=B0C calorie</li>
<li>15&nbsp;=C2=B0C calorie</li>
<li>20&nbsp;=C2=B0C calorie</li>
<li>Mean calorie</li>
<li>International Steam Table calorie (1929)</li>
<li>International Steam Table calorie (1956)</li>
<li>IUNS calorie (Committee on Nomenclature of the International Union of N=
utritional Sciences)</li>
</ul>
<p>The calorie is outdated and commonly replaced by the SI-unit Joule.</p>
<h3>Joule</h3>
<p>The unit of heat in the SI-system the Joule is</p>
<ul>
<li>a unit of energy equal to the work done when a force of one newton acts=
 through a distance of one meter</li>
<li>4.184 joule of heat energy (or one calorie) is required to raise the te=
mperature of a unit weight <i>(1 g) </i>of water from <i>0 <sup>o</sup>C</i=
> to <i>1 <sup>o</sup>C</i>, or from<i> 31 <sup>o</sup>F to 33.8 <sup>o</su=
p>F</i></li>
<li><i>1 J (Joule) =3D 0.1020 kpm =3D 2.778=C3=9710<sup>-7</sup> kWh =3D 2.=
389=C3=9710<sup>-4</sup> kcal =3D 0.7376 ft.lb<sub>f</sub> =3D 1 kg.m<sup>2=
</sup>/s<sup>2</sup> =3D 1 watt second =3D 1 Nm =3D 9.478=C3=9710<sup>-4</s=
up> Btu</i></li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://www.engineeringtoolbox.com/unit-converter-d_185.html=
" title=3D"Unit converter ">Converting between heat and energy units</a></l=
i>
</ul>
</div>
